# Project Conventions

## Clean Code

- Single responsibility: one function does one thing.
- Functions stay short (under 30 lines). If longer, extract.
- Guard clauses over nested conditionals. Return early.
- Names describe intent: `getUserById` not `getData`, `isValid` not `check`.
- No magic numbers or strings. Use named constants.
- Delete dead code. Do not comment it out.

## Naming Consistency

- Pick one naming convention per category and apply it uniformly:
  - Functions and variables: `camelCase` or `snake_case` (match language idiom).
  - Types and classes: `PascalCase`.
  - Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`.
- File names match the primary export or class they contain.
- Test files are co-located with source or in a parallel test directory.

## Error Handling

- Handle errors explicitly. Never silently swallow exceptions or error codes.
- Use the language's idiomatic error mechanism (exceptions, Result types, error codes).
- Add context when propagating errors — what operation failed and why.
- Validate inputs at system boundaries. Do not trust external data.

## Testing

- Write tests alongside implementation. At minimum: happy path, error path, edge cases.
- One assertion concept per test. Clear test names describe the scenario.
- Use the project's test framework. Follow its conventions for file naming and structure.
- Test error paths, not just success paths.
- Use temporary directories for filesystem tests. Never write to fixed paths.

## Dependencies

- Minimize dependency count. Prefer standard library solutions when reasonable.
- Pin dependency versions. Update deliberately, not automatically.
- Audit new dependencies for maintenance status and security.

## Security

- No secrets in code. Use environment variables or secret managers.
- Validate and sanitize all external input.
- Use parameterized queries for database access. No string concatenation.
- Follow the principle of least privilege for file access and API permissions.

## Code Organization

- Separate concerns: data access, business logic, and presentation in distinct layers.
- Keep modules focused. If a file exceeds 300 lines, consider splitting.
- Group related functionality together. Alphabetical ordering within groups.
- Public API surface should be minimal. Hide implementation details.


## Project-Specific Conventions

- Use clippy::pedantic with #![deny(warnings)] and #![deny(unsafe_code)] in all crates
- Format all code with rustfmt (cargo fmt) — no custom rustfmt.toml overrides unless agreed upon
- Use thiserror for typed error enums in iris-core (one error enum per module). Use miette for diagnostic error reports in iris-cli
- Follow layered architecture: transport (MCP JSON-RPC) → service (business logic) → storage (SQLite, HNSW). No layer may skip a level
- All async code uses tokio runtime. Use #[tokio::test] for async tests. Never block the async runtime with synchronous I/O
- Every public function and type must have a /// doc comment. Module-level docs use //! comments. Include doc tests for non-trivial APIs
- Use tracing for all instrumentation. Add #[instrument] to public functions. Use spans for MCP tool calls, prefetch operations, and index queries
- Prefer community-standard crates for solved problems (rmcp, fastembed, rusqlite, comrak, serde, tokio). Build custom only for novel mechanisms (session shadow, prefetch engine, budget manager)
- Error types must be matchable in library crates. Use #[from] for automatic conversions. Add .context() with miette for CLI-facing errors
- Integration tests go in tests/ and test against real SQLite databases and HNSW indexes — no mocking storage layers
- All dependencies must pass cargo-audit and cargo-deny checks. Run these in CI as blocking gates
- Use just as the task runner. All CI commands must be runnable locally via just (e.g., just test, just lint, just coverage)
- Naming: snake_case for functions/modules, CamelCase for types, SCREAMING_SNAKE for constants. Follow Rust API Guidelines (RFC 430)
- Keep iris-core free of transport concerns. It must not depend on rmcp or any MCP types directly — only iris-mcp bridges the protocol
- Session shadow, prefetch cache, and budget manager are the three novel subsystems. These get the most thorough testing and documentation

## AI Agent Tips

- Run just validate before every commit — it chains fmt check, clippy, test, and audit in one command
- Use RUST_LOG=iris=debug,rmcp=info for development logging. The tracing-subscriber EnvFilter respects this
- fastembed downloads models on first use (~90MB for all-MiniLM-L6-v2). Set FASTEMBED_CACHE_PATH to share across dev machines
- The DESIGN.md [VALIDATE] markers are invitations to web-search before implementing — use brave-search MCP to verify claims
- cargo-llvm-cov generates HTML coverage reports — open target/llvm-cov/html/index.html after running just coverage